\begin{document}$$ y^* = {\text{origin}} + {\text{marker}} + {\text{error}} $$\end{document}where y* stands for adjusted means saved from the previous model. Origin is a factor with four classes to identify the origin of each genotype in the sample: three corresponding to the genotype groups “SAR”, “BNA” and “NOR”, and the fourth to the group “Standards”. Marker is a factor with two levels, for DNA fragment present or absent. Its association with the trait was tested by a (partial) t test, testing the additional variation explained by a marker after correction for origin. The resulting P values were converted into q values (see below). The proportion of genetic variation explained by each marker was calculated as the relative increase in R2 when the marker is added to the model. Finally, we constructed multi-QTL models by applying stepwise selection to the set of significant markers found in the previous single-marker regression model (1):\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
